text.tspan: DTMF stands for Dual-Tone Multi-Frequency. It's a way
of creating special tones to control the phone system.

flowRoot.flowPara: What are the A, B, C, and D keys?

Those keys are present in the DTMF specification, but they're never used in normal consumer phones. The tones that A, B, C, and D generate are often repurposed as control codes. For example, in the US Military, they were used to set the priority of the call.
DTMF is a form of "In Band Signalling". It's called In Band because it is transmitted in the same channel as the telephone data (your voice!).
Both your voice and the DTMF tones share the same line. The telephone system simply listens to your phone line for the tones. If it hears the tones, it takes some action.

DTMF is not the only in band signalling system the phone company used. Single tones were also utilized. The most famous of these tones is the 2600Hz tone, which signalled that a line was idle and another call could be placed. Phreakers used this tone to trick the system into thinking a line was open, allowing them to make free long distance calls!
